<body>
	<div class="banner">
		<center><font color="white" size="16px" face="arial">BaeR</font></center>
	</div>
	<div align="center" class="main-content">
		<div class="spacer">
	</div><br>			<label class="collapse_ACT" for="_1"><font size="5px">BaeR transcriptional activity</font></label>
				<input id="_1" type="checkbox">
				<div class="ACT"><br><ul><li>The RR-bound 32P was stably retained for the A1 group RRs such as pArcA , pCpxR , pCusR , pKdpE , and pNarL but was rapidly released for the A2 group RRs , including pBaeR , pCheB , pCheY , pCreB , pDcuR , pNarP , pNtrC , pTorR , pUhpA , pYehT , and pYfhA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15522865" target="_blank">15522865</a>]<br></li>
<li>The phosphorylation level was from 1 % to 10 % for TorR , PhoB , CusR , BasR , RstA , UvrY , ArcA , BaeR , NtrC , KdpE , UhpA , and PhoP ( in decreasing order ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15522865" target="_blank">15522865</a>]<br></li>
<li>The trans-phos-phorylation was experimentally demonstrated in vitro , for the first time , for 9 pairs , CusS-CusR , RstB-RstA , YedV-YedW , BaeS-BaeR , YehU-YehT , YfhK-YfhA , HydH-HydG , BasSBasR , and CreC-CreB ( see Fig. 3 ) , supporting the predicted HK-RR pairs .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15522865" target="_blank">15522865</a>]<br></li>
<li>A total of 30 sensor HKs , including as yet uncharacterized puta - tive HKs ( BaeS , BasS , CreC , CusS , HydH , RstB , YedV , and YfhK ) , and a total of 34 RRs , including putative RRs ( BaeR , BasR , CreB , CusR , HydG , RstA , YedW , YfhA , YgeK , and YhjB ) , have been suggested to exist in Esche - richia coli .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15522865" target="_blank">15522865</a>]<br></li>
<li>Trans-phosphorylation of presumed cog - nate RRs by HKs was detected , for the first time , for eight pairs , BaeS-BaeR , BasS-BasR , CreC-CreB , CusS-CusR , HydH-HydG , RstB-RstA , YedV-YedW , and YfhK-YfhA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15522865" target="_blank">15522865</a>]<br></li>
<li>e Putative Response Regulator BaeR Stimulates Multidrug Th Resistance of Escherichia coli via a Novel Multidrug Exporter System , MdtABC Satoshi Nagakubo ,1,2 Kunihiko Nishino ,1,2,3 Takahiro Hirata ,1,2,3 and Akihito Yamaguchi1 ,2,3 * Department of Cell Membrane Biology , Institute of Scientiﬁc and Industrial Research , Osaka University , Ibaraki ,1 and CREST , Japan Science and Technology Corporation , Osaka 567-0047 ,3 and Faculty of Pharmaceutical Science , Osaka University , Suita , Osaka 565-0871 ,2 Japan Received 19 February 2002/Accepted 29 April 2002 Overproduction of the response-regulator BaeR confers resistance to novobiocin and bile salts in a acrAB mutant by stimulating drug exporter gene expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107133" target="_blank">12107133</a>]<br></li>
<li>Incubation of cells with novobiocin followed by a chromatographic assay for intracellular drug showed that overproduced BaeR decreased drastically the drug accumulation , presumably via increased active efﬂux .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>In our experiments , in which only the activator BaeR and not its putative target , MdtABCD , was overexpressed , there was no detectable change in resistance to these latter compounds .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , disruption of yegO completely abolished the increase in both novobiocin and deoxycholate MICs caused by BaeR ( Table 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>Also , although the increase in novobiocin resistance induced by BaeR in our experiments was similar to the increase caused by MdtABCD overexpression observed by Nishino and Yama-guchi ( 26 ) , resistance to deoxycholate in cells overexpressing only BaeR went up only eightfold .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>Details are shown in Supplementary Table S2 , but briefly this consisted of 184 genes that could be divided into the following categories : repressed by Fur , 63 ; activated by Fur , 15 ; repressed by CpxR , 21 ; activated by CpxR , 37 ; repressed by SoxS , 1 ; activated by SoxS , 23 ; repressed by OxyR , 2 ; activated by OxyR , 16 ; activated by CusR , 6 ; activated by BaeR , 9 ; repressed by Zur , 4 ; repressed by ArsR , 3 ; activated by ZraR , 3 ; activated by ZntR , 1 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22016571" target="_blank">22016571</a>]<br></li>
				<label class="ACT_collapse_similarity" for="act_similarity_12">
Statistical modelling of the transcriptomic data generated from the Zn shift focused on the role of ten key regulators ; ArsR , BaeR , CpxR , CusR , Fur , OxyR , SoxS , ZntR , ZraR and Zur .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22016571" target="_blank">22016571</a>]<br></label>
<input id="act_similarity_12", type="checkbox">
<div class="ACT_similar">
<li>The analysis of the transcriptomic data generated from the Zn shift focused on the role of ten key regulators : ArsR , BaeR , CpxR , CusR , Fur , OxyR , SoxS , ZntR , ZraR and Zur .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22016571" target="_blank">22016571</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>While the profiles of the ` monotonic ' regulators BaeR , CpxR , Zur and CusR are compatible with the predicted profile from the dynamic time-course dataset , neither Fur nor SoxS exhibits the transient behaviour predicted from the dynamic data .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22016571" target="_blank">22016571</a>]<br></li>
<li>Inferred activity profiles of regulators BaeR , CpxR , CusR , Fur , SoxS and Zur during adaptation from Zn deprivation to Zn excess : TFinfer software predictions on the temporally resolved data collected upon addition of 200 mM Zn to Zn-depleted continuous cultures .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22016571" target="_blank">22016571</a>]<br></li>
<li>Inferred activity profiles of regulators BaeR , CpxR , CusR , Fur , SoxS and Zur at steady states with different Zn concentrations .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22016571" target="_blank">22016571</a>]<br></li>
<li>Alternatively , even low levels of activity of nonphosphorylated BaeR might be sufﬁcient when the protein is present in large excess .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>The transformants obtained were used to test the changes in - galacto-sidase activity in response to the induction of BaeR synthesis with 0.2 % arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>Plasmid pNNyeg2 , which contained this DNA fragment , was assayed as described above and produced a similar increase in - galactosidase activity in response to the induction of BaeR synthesis ( Fig. 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>When cells carrying pBADBaeR and pNNyeg1 were incubated with 0.2 % L-arabi-nose for 4 h to induce production of BaeR , the speciﬁc - ga-lactosidase activity in the culture increased approximately 45 times compared to that of the cells grown without arabinose ( Fig. 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>- Galactosidase activity , expressed from the lacZ gene in pNN387 , increased four to ﬁve times in response to the induction of BaeR with 0.2 % arabinose in the cells doubly transformed with pBADBaeR and either pNNyicO-H or pN-NyicO-R ( Fig. 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>BaeR and BaeS were shown to exhibit the in vitro phosphotransfer reaction in the presence of ATP ( 24 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>It seemed likely that in cells carrying pTrcBaeR , overexpressed BaeR was causing the transcriptional activation of genes involved in multidrug resistance .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , the presence of baeS does not seem to be required for the activity of overexpressed BaeR in these cells .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , we found that the presence of the sensor kinase BaeS was not required for the full activity of the overexpressed BaeR in intact cells .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>On the other hand , in the case of mdtA gene , the upregulation by indole reduced but remained in the baeSR-deletion strains and completely abolished in the baeSR-cpxAR double-deletion strains ( Fig. 2B ) , suggesting that the unknown indole signalling pathway via factor X from CpxA may also upregulate mdtABC independent to BaeR therefore indole can stimulate mdtABC in the baeSR knockout strain , whereas indole can not stimulate mdtABC in the baeSR-cpxAR double knockout strain because factor X does not work in the absence of CpxA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>Hence , the Pcas activity seems to act as an `` ON/OFF switch '' of the CRISPR-mediated immunity .22 In addition , the BaeSR two-component system has been shown to be involved in the regulation of the CRISPR-Cas system .23,24 The transport of an aberrantly folded protein through the membrane leads to the phosphorylation of the response-regulator BaeR , which binds at the Pcas promoter region and activates the Cascade operon .24 Although the exact mechanism of the BaeSR-dependent regulation is not known , the results could point to a specific envelope stress-dependent induction of the CRISPR-Cas system .25 To understand the biological meaning of a highly conserved and functional but tightly repressed CRISPR system in E. coli , we initiated studies to identify the condition ( s ) , which induces the CRISPR system .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23392250" target="_blank">23392250</a>]<br></li>
<li>Involvement of BaeSR two-component system in Zn ( II ) - dependent activation of the spy promoter phorylated BaeR directly binds to the target promoter to activate its transcription ( Hirakawa et al. , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17884222" target="_blank">17884222</a>]<br></li>
<li>BaeR thus directly binds to and stimulates the transcriptional activity of the mdtA promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>As shown in Fig. 2 , BaeR overexpression increased the amounts of mdtA , mdtB , mdtC , and mdtD mRNA by factors of about 7.4 , 6.6 , 4.5 , and 2.8 , respectively .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107133" target="_blank">12107133</a>]<br></li>
<li>To test whether this sequence is required for gene induction by BaeR , we investigated the effect of deletion of the BaeR-binding motif on gene induction .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>Puriﬁed BaeR and CpxR proteins without acetylphosphate treatment also bind to the promoter regions of these genes , while the concentrations of the non-treated puriﬁed proteins required for the electrophoretic mobility shifts were higher than those of phosphorylated ones , indicating that the signiﬁcant part of the puriﬁed proteins might be intrinsically phosphorylated ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>Polyhistidine-tagged BaeR and CpxR proteins were puriﬁed on Ni-chelated resin , followed by phosphorylation with acetylphosphate .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>BaeR and CpxR were overproduced as His6-BaeR and His6-CpxR by IPTG induction , and then puriﬁed on Ni afﬁnity resin ( Amersham Pharmacia Biotech ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>The results suggest that BaeR primarily binds to the proximal region to play a major role in the upregulation of exporter gene expression , and CpxR binds to multiple distal regions to modulate the effect of BaeR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>As shown in Fig. 3 , the effect of BaeR overexpression on acrD and mdtA gene expression ( about 20 - and 146-fold increase ) was greater than that of CpxR ( about 7.3 - and 2.5-fold increase ) in wild-type cells .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>The effect of baeSR and cpxAR deletion on the CpxR and BaeR overexpression-induced upregulation of acrD and mdtA gene expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>CpxR appears , in this case , to be an enhancer of the primary regulator BaeR via binding to multiple sites in the acrD and mdtA promoter regions [ 22 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16487683" target="_blank">16487683</a>]<br></li>
<li>The electrophoretic mobilities of the DNA fragments of the acrD and mdtA promoter regions shifted on the addition of phosphorylated BaeR and CpxR , whereas that of emrK ( negative control ) was not affected ( Fig. 5 ) , indicating the BaeR and CpxR proteins directly bind to the promoter regions of the acrD and mdtA genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>The activated BaeR and CpxR directly bind to different sites in the acrD and mdtA promoter regions , resulting the upregulation of the expression of acrD and mdtABC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>BaeR and CpxR activated by indole upregulate target genes by direct binding to the promoter regions , while BaeR is essential and CpxR modulates the BaeR action.There may be an additional signalling pathway from CpxA via unknown factor X to upregulate the mdtA gene .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>BaeR alone upregulates the expression of target genes without CpxR , whereas CpxR enhances the effect of BaeR by direct binding to the multiple regions upstream of the BaeR-binding site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>To determine the effect of overexpression of BaeR and CpxR , 0.5 mM IPTG was added to induce these response-regulator genes when cultures reached an OD600 of 0.4 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>Based on the observation that CpxAR-mediated induction required BaeSR system , whereas BaeSR-mediated induction did not require CpxAR , they implied that BaeR is the primary regulator and CpxR enhances its function .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17884222" target="_blank">17884222</a>]<br></li>
<li>These observations indicate that BaeR is a primary regulator , and CpxR enhances the effect of BaeR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of the main activator ( BaeR for acrD and mtdA , OmpR for ompC ) , CpxR-P can not act as a transcriptional-activator .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16487683" target="_blank">16487683</a>]<br></li>
<li>Contributions of AcrD and MdtABC to multidrug resistance mediated by overexpression of BaeR , CpxR , and OmpR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12618449" target="_blank">12618449</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcriptional level CpxR-P not only modulates the action of different regulators , such as BaeR , Lrp and OmpR , by binding to the same regulatory sequences ( see above ) , but it also represses the gene transcription of other signaling systems , such as σE and Aer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16487683" target="_blank">16487683</a>]<br></li>
<li>Indole signalling is transmitted via BaeSR and CpxAR , two-component signal transduction pathways , to cause the induction of acrD and mdtABC gene expression We previously reported that the acrD gene is upregulated by response-regulators BaeR and CpxR ( Hirakawa et al. , 2003a ) , and that the mdtEF gene is upregulated by EvgA ( Nishino and Yamaguchi , 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>phorylate and then transfer their phosphate to their cognate response-regulators , BaeR and CpxR , respectively .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17172327" target="_blank">17172327</a>]<br></li>
<li>One explanation for this observation could be that cross-talk occurs between these two-component regulators , in which the BaeS and/or CpxA sensor kinases are able to phosphorylate both BaeR and CpxR in response to activating cues .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12354228" target="_blank">12354228</a>]<br></li>
<li>BaeR and EvgA also upregulate the mdtABC and emrKY genes respectively ( Nishino and Yamaguchi , 2001b ; Nagakubo et al. , 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>In our previous study , we found that EvgA and BaeR upregulate the expression of drug exporter genes such as emrKY , yhiUV , and mdtABC ( 13 , 17 , 18 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12618449" target="_blank">12618449</a>]<br></li>
<li>BaeR did not increase the expression of 17 genes in the phoBR strain or the expression of 21 genes in the creBC strain that were induced by BaeR in W3110 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our data suggested that BaeR activated transcription of the mdtABCD genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>BaeR activates promoters of the yicO and ygcL genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>BaeR overproduction activated 59 genes related to two-component signal transduction , chemotactic responses , ﬂagellar biosynthesis , maltose transport , and multidrug transport , and BaeR overproduction also repressed the expression of the ibpA and ibpB genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>BaeR increased the expression of malE , which encodes a maltose-binding protein , and malFGK , which encode the translocation complex .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>The expression of 11 gene clusters was increased by BaeR overproduction .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>Gene clusters whose expression was increased by BaeR overproduction .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>Lanes 1 , 5 and 9 , no regulator ; BaeR protein : lanes 2 , 6 and 10 , 0.5 mM ; lanes 3 , 7 and 11 , 1.1 mM ; lanes 4 , 8 and 12 , 2.3 mM .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>This pathway seems to be independent to BaeR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>This system is also stimulated by overproduction of the response-regulator BaeR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107133" target="_blank">12107133</a>]<br></li>
<li>Here we show that the BaeS sensor kinase and BaeR response-regulator also control expression of spy in response to envelope stress .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12354228" target="_blank">12354228</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , pBADBaeR did not increase the MICs of various other agents , including nalidixic acid , norﬂoxacin , and SDS , against WZM120 , even in the presence of arabinose ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>Introduction of the plasmid isolated from this strain ( the plasmid is called pTrcBaeR on the basis of results described below ) into fresh AG100A cells resulted in the same phenotype of novobiocin resistance : MICs increased 4 - and 16-fold over those against the recipient strain in the absence and presence of IPTG , respectively ( Table 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>The knockout strains were transformed with pTrcBaeR or an empty vector for control , and the MICs of novobiocin and deoxycholate were determined in the presence of 100 M IPTG ( Table 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , when pTrcBaeR was used to transform AG100 cells , which express the AcrAB pump , no effect on novobiocin resistance was observed ( Table 2 ) , presumably because AG100 already was highly resistant to this drug , whose MIC against it was 160 g/ml .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>pTrcBaeR was also found to increase the resistance of both AG100A and AG100 cells to deoxycholate about eightfold .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_DOM" for="_2"><font size="5px">BaeR protein domains</font></label>
				<input id="_2" type="checkbox">
				<div class="DOM"><br><ul><li>The observed interaction between the mdtA promoter and BaeR in vitro ( Fig. 5 ) most likely involved unphosphorylated protein , as response regulators usually possess autophosphatase activity that limits the lifetime of the phosphorylated states ( 40 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>BaeR increased the expression of three other clusters , one of which contains the amn and yeeN genes , one of which contains the gsp and yghU genes , and one of which contains the yieI and yieJ genes ( Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_EVO" for="_3"><font size="5px">BaeR evolution</font></label>
				<input id="_3" type="checkbox">
				<div class="EVO"><br><ul><li>Moreover , expression of ygcL was shown to be regulated by BaeR , a member of the two-component regulatory system BaeSR , controlling multidrug transporters ( Baranova and Nikaido , 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20132443" target="_blank">20132443</a>]<br></li>
<li>BaeR exhibits sequence similarity to the response regulators and is likely to constitute a two-component regulatory system with a sensor kinase , BaeS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
