<li>We therefore think it likely that BaeS and BaeR control expression of additional , distinct envelope stress adaptive factors that have not yet been identiﬁed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12354228" target="_blank">12354228</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression control of mdtABCD genes by BaeR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107133" target="_blank">12107133</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , it appears that BaeR must control expression of genes in addition to spy that are important in withstanding overexpression of misfolded PapG .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12354228" target="_blank">12354228</a>]<br></li>
<li>BaeR increased the expression of malE , which encodes a maltose-binding protein , and malFGK , which encode the translocation complex .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>Enhanced expression of gene clusters due to BaeR overproduction .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>Several genes up-regulated by BaeR overproduction , including genes for maltose-transport , chemotactic responses , and ﬂagellar biosynthesis , required an intact PhoBR or CreBC two-component regulatory system for up-regulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>BaeR overproduction activated 59 genes related to two-component signal-transduction , chemotactic responses , ﬂagellar biosynthesis , maltose-transport , and multidrug-transport , and BaeR overproduction also repressed the expression of the ibpA and ibpB genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>We discovered that overproduction of BaeR affects the expression of gene clusters related to two-component signal-transduction , maltose-transport , chemotatic responses , ﬂagellar biosynthesis , and multi-drug-transport .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>Deletion of both mdtC and mdtD completely abolished the elevation of drug-resistance by BaeR , demonstrating that mdtC plays a crucial role in this resistance .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>Hence , the Pcas activity seems to act as an `` ON/OFF switch '' of the CRISPR-mediated immunity .22 In addition , the BaeSR two-component system has been shown to be involved in the regulation of the CRISPR-Cas system .23,24 The transport of an aberrantly folded protein through the membrane leads to the phosphorylation of the response regulator BaeR , which binds at the Pcas promoter region and activates the Cascade operon .24 Although the exact mechanism of the BaeSR-dependent regulation is not known , the results could point to a specific envelope stress-dependent induction of the CRISPR-Cas system .25 To understand the biological meaning of a highly conserved and functional but tightly repressed CRISPR system in E. coli , we initiated studies to identify the condition ( s ) , which induces the CRISPR system .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23392250" target="_blank">23392250</a>]<br></li>
<li>It seemed likely that in cells carrying pTrcBaeR , overexpressed BaeR was causing the transcriptional activation of genes involved in multidrug-resistance .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>e Putative Response Regulator BaeR Stimulates Multidrug Th Resistance of Escherichia coli via a Novel Multidrug Exporter System , MdtABC Satoshi Nagakubo ,1,2 Kunihiko Nishino ,1,2,3 Takahiro Hirata ,1,2,3 and Akihito Yamaguchi1 ,2,3 * Department of Cell Membrane Biology , Institute of Scientiﬁc and Industrial Research , Osaka University , Ibaraki ,1 and CREST , Japan Science and Technology Corporation , Osaka 567-0047 ,3 and Faculty of Pharmaceutical Science , Osaka University , Suita , Osaka 565-0871 ,2 Japan Received 19 February 2002/Accepted 29 April 2002 Overproduction of the response regulator BaeR confers resistance to novobiocin and bile salts in a acrAB mutant by stimulating drug exporter gene-expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107133" target="_blank">12107133</a>]<br></li>
<li>Overproduction of BaeR , in the background of a deﬁciency of the E. coli major multidrug exporter AcrB , confers resistance against - lactams , novobiocin , sodium dodecyl sulfate , and bile salts .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>DISCUSSION In this study , we showed that overexpression of the response regulator BaeR stimulates the drug-resistance phenotype by upregulating the expression of a novel RND-type drug exporter , MdtABC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107133" target="_blank">12107133</a>]<br></li>
				<label class="RP_collapse_similarity" for="rp_similarity_19">
The putative response regulator BaeR stimulates multidrug-resistance of Escherichia coli via a novel multidrug exporter system , MdtABC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12949086" target="_blank">12949086</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12670992" target="_blank">12670992</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12618449" target="_blank">12618449</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12951338" target="_blank">12951338</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14973023" target="_blank">14973023</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15659689" target="_blank">15659689</a>]<br></label>
