			<label class="collapse_TU" for="_6"><font size="5px">Transcription unit regulated by BaeR</font></label>
				<input id="_6" type="checkbox">
				<div class="TU"><br><ul><li>Transcription of CRISPR-1 and casA -- E is repressed by H-NS [ 31 ] and de-repressed by LeuO [ 32 ] or BaeR [ 33 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21699496" target="_blank">21699496</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcriptional level CpxR-P not only modulates the action of different regulators , such as BaeR , Lrp and OmpR , by binding to the same regulatory sequences ( see above ) , but it also represses the gene transcription of other signaling systems , such as σE and Aer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16487683" target="_blank">16487683</a>]<br></li>
<li>The order of these values is consistent with the transcription of mdtABCD from the same promoter of the mdt-bae operon under the control of BaeR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107133" target="_blank">12107133</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is thought that both mdtABCD and baeSR are regulated by BaeR , because they form an operon and are transcribed from the same promoter ( Fig. 1 ) ( 6 , 36 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>Novobiocin accumulation is reduced in acrAB cells overexpressing BaeR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>We found that mdtD was not involved in novobiocin and deoxycholate resistance , since the resistance of the cells overexpressing BaeR was not compromised by the deletion of this gene .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>We found that BaeR increased the expression of the outer membrane channel tolC gene ( 7.9-fold as determined by microarray analysis and 12-fold as determined by qRT-PCR ) , which is required for the function of the MdtABC and AcrD multidrug export systems ( Table 2 ) ( 41 , 42 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>BaeR is the response regulator of a putative two-component system , which also includes the sensor kinase BaeS , encoded by a gene located upstream of baeR ( 24 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>BaeR overproduction increased the expression of baeS , which encodes a cognate sensor of the BaeR response regulator ( 37 ) and is located downstream of mdtABCD ( 42 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>BaeR also increased the expression of the creB response regulator gene of the creBC two-component system .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>Overproduction of BaeR also increased expression of the CreB regulon ( 4 ) , including expression of creD , malE , yidS , and yieI ( Table 2 ) and the creB response regulator gene ( 2.6-fold increase as determined by microarray analysis ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>Induction of the xenobiotic exporter genes acrD and mdtA is indeed mediated by CpxR and BaeR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16487683" target="_blank">16487683</a>]<br></li>
<li>As shown in Fig. 3 , the effect of BaeR overexpression on acrD and mdtA gene expression ( about 20 - and 146-fold increase ) was greater than that of CpxR ( about 7.3 - and 2.5-fold increase ) in wild-type cells .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition , elimination of BaeR compromises the ability of E. coli to withstand some of these same envelope stresses ( Fig. 7 ) and this can not be explained by reduced expression of spy , the only known Bae-regulated gene .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12354228" target="_blank">12354228</a>]<br></li>
<li>BaeS and BaeR do not affect expression of other known Cpx-regulated genes , however , baeR cpxR double mutants show increased sensitivity to envelope stresses relative to either single mutant alone .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12354228" target="_blank">12354228</a>]<br></li>
<li>BaeS and BaeR do not affect expression of other Cpx-regulated genes , but baeR cpxR double mutants show increased sensitivity to envelope stresses beyond those of individual baeR or cpxR mutants .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12354228" target="_blank">12354228</a>]<br></li>
<li>In order to determine whether the expression of the mdtABC genes is controlled by BaeR , we performed Northern blot analysis with a DNA fragment containing the mdtC region as a probe .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107133" target="_blank">12107133</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression control of mdtABCD genes by BaeR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107133" target="_blank">12107133</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , it appears that BaeR must control expression of genes in addition to spy that are important in withstanding overexpression of misfolded PapG .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12354228" target="_blank">12354228</a>]<br></li>
<li>Finally , the expression of two other genes , yicO and ygcL , was shown to be regulated by BaeR , but it is not known if they play any roles in resistance .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>On the other hand , the expression of the yhiUV , emrA , emrE , macA , and ydhE genes was not affected by BaeR overexpression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107133" target="_blank">12107133</a>]<br></li>
<li>Overproduction of BaeR induced the expression of 40 genes in the phoBR strain and the expression of 38 genes in the creBC strain by more than twofold .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>BaeR did not increase the expression of 17 genes in the phoBR strain or the expression of 21 genes in the creBC strain that were induced by BaeR in W3110 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>Overexpression of BaeR did not increase the expression levels of these genes without the BaeR-binding motifs ( Table 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>BaeR controls the expression of acrD and mdtABC multidrug efﬂux system genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>Searches of the regions upstream ( 400 bp ) of all 59 genes whose expression was increased by BaeR overexpression did not reveal sequences matching the consensus sequence other than spy , mdtA , acrD , and ycaC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>BaeR increased the expression of malE , which encodes a maltose-binding protein , and malFGK , which encode the translocation complex .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>BaeR increased the expression of three other clusters , one of which contains the amn and yeeN genes , one of which contains the gsp and yghU genes , and one of which contains the yieI and yieJ genes ( Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>Gene clusters whose expression was increased by BaeR overproduction .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul></div><br>
